    {
      "content": "# Scenario Information\n\nWe’re telling the story of a frontier firm operating globally in the pharmaceutical sector, whose ambition is to accelerate innovation, lower cost, and improve outcomes at scale.\n\nThey are not defined by a single industry slice. While grounded in drug discovery and manufacturing, their work spans the pharmaceutical lifecycle—from research and development through production, commercialization, and market access—giving us a narrative that can extend across verticals…\n\nAt its core, this is a company committed to solving complex, real-world problems that ultimately make the world a better place: Bringing life-improving medications to market faster, scaling production responsibly, and delivering better outcomes for patients: bringing life-improving medications to market faster.\n\n# Where they are today\n\nThe defining characteristic of this company is how they operate and the deep integration of AI across their business.\n\n# Human ambition is the starting point\n\n- Leaders, researchers, operators, and developers set direction and make decisions\n- AI operates across the company as a continuous layer that connects work, accelerates insight, and executes behind the scenes\n- This intelligence layer becomes a strategic asset, allowing them to move faster and operate more competitively in market\n\n# Work happens in connected teams, not in silos\n\n<Company> works, builds, operates, observes, and optimizes its business with AI working across functions\n\nMultiple roles interact in a shared system, with AI helping coordinate and carry context across each step\n\nThe connected AI-native lifecycle allows them to build intelligent systems, observe and govern them in real time, and continuously optimize for performance and cost\n\n# AI is embedded throughout the business process\n\nNot a separate tool—it shows up inside workflows: creating artifacts, analyzing signals, coordinating actions, and automating tasks\n\nThe experience spans everything from conversational AI to autonomous execution, with security and trust integrated into the flow\n\n# How they got here\n\nSome months ago, <Company> made a deliberate strategic pivot to reframe how they think about AI. This pivot was grounded in a new operating philosophy: AI must do more than make us more efficient—it must make us extraordinary.\n\nThis pivot builds on three decades of disciplined growth and capability building. Founded in the early 1990s, <Company> began as a regional generics manufacturer with a clear mission: Make safe, effective medications more accessible globally. Over time, it scaled to a global enterprise operating in more than 100 countries with a diverse product portfolio, spanning over the counter (OTC), specialty therapeutics, and consumer health products.\n\n# The demo hook\n\nWhen we encounter <Company>, they are reacting to the breaking news that a direct competitor has announced a new product launch in a therapeutic category where the company already has a leading position, offering a longer-lasting injection with fewer doses and an earlier market entry timeline.\n\nWith the announcement, the expected time-to-market advantage is reduced, with the competitor expected to launch ahead of <Company>’s next-generation product, creating immediate pressure and forcing the company to adjust its operations in real time, but its current systems aren’t equipped to respond at that pace.\n\nThis forces a critical leadership question: Can <Company> respond fast enough to close the timing gap and defend market share, without introducing operational or regulatory risk?\n\nWith this backdrop, the team moves quickly to assemble a cross-functional team:\n\n- They pull together data across the business to understand launch impact, the new competitive demand signal and timeline shift\n- They identify where they can unlock operational systems to deliver at speed and scale, with supply chain and capacity emerging as the primary constraint\n- They define the requirements and solution design for real-time demand response based on capacity constraints, with fully autonomous / long running agents within defined governance and control boundaries to meet the accelerated timeline\n\nThis kicks off the remaining demos, which explore how they build, secure, govern, operate, and optimize this AI-first supply chain system. We see:\n\n- Increase batch release velocity and manufacturing throughput through AI-driven scheduling\n- Capture early market share by dynamically allocating supply to high-demand markets\n- Reduce time-to-first-prescription and accelerate patient access to life-improving therapies\n- Maintain continuous GMP compliance and inspection readiness under compressed timelines\n- Sustain competitive market leadership under accelerated competitive pressure\n- Accelerate payor and formulary readiness to enable rapid market access",
      "role": "tool",
      "tool_call_id": "call_780BBAHKA4P1QVaMuq2I8xlY"
    },
    {
      "content": "# Triage in GitHub Copilot App\n\n## Row 0 [~20s]\n**Narrative:** - Competitor launch creates pressure to respond fast\n- Company already has a portfolio of internal apps\n- Goal is to decide where an agentic update will matter most\n**Actions:** - Open with the business trigger\n- Frame the company as already running several internal apps\n- Set up the need to choose the best insertion point for agentic software\n**Screenshot:** .cutready/screenshots/20260610_001556_051_2.jpg\n\n## Row 1 [~25s]\n**Narrative:** - Start in GitHub Copilot App\n- Use home, my work, automations, and quick chats to orient the team\n- Move quickly from broad status to active software work\n**Actions:** - Tour home, my work, automations, and quick chats\n- Keep the pace brisk\n- Use the app as the team control surface, not a feature tour\n**Screenshot:** .cutready/screenshots/20260610_001610_115_6.jpg\n\n## Row 2 [~30s]\n**Narrative:** - Review the active app collection tied to supply chain and operations\n- Compare where delays, manual work, or planning friction show up\n- Narrow to the app or service with the highest upside\n**Actions:** - Open the active project or app collection\n- Show the relevant apps, services, or repos in play\n- Highlight the one area where agent behavior can help first\n**Screenshot:** .cutready/screenshots/20260610_002152_134_10.jpg\n\n## Row 3 [~30s]\n**Narrative:** - Use sessions, worktrees, rubber duck, and canvas to shape the response\n- Turn portfolio discussion into a concrete engineering path\n- Keep the focus on what needs to change in the chosen app\n**Actions:** - Show sessions and worktrees\n- Briefly visit rubber duck and canvas\n- Use each feature to move from discussion to scoped implementation\n**Screenshot:** .cutready/screenshots/20260610_003812_573_14.jpg\n\n## Row 4 [~35s]\n**Narrative:** - Land on the first functional addition\n- Identify the first agent, skill, or Copilot Studio artifact to bring into the engineering flow\n- Use that as the handoff into local development\n**Actions:** - Land on the concrete next step\n- Show the first agent, skill, or Copilot Studio artifact selected from the app portfolio\n- End on the handoff into code and agent development\n**Screenshot:** .cutready/screenshots/20260610_003833_787_18.jpg\n\n",
      "role": "tool",
      "tool_call_id": "call_Jc8kdUsSYw5XYkc9hcn0lmrt"
    },
    {
      "content": "## Yes. A good way to make this demo feel real is to give the team a small portfolio of internal apps that already exist, then use Copilot App to pick the one where an agentic upgrade has the clearest business payoff.\n\nFor this scenario, I would keep the app ideas tightly tied to the competitor shock, supply constraints, and regulatory pressure.\n\n## Best framing\n\nThe story is not \"what app can AI improve in general?\"\nIt is:\n\n- competitor launch changed the timeline\n- leadership needs a response now\n- supply chain and capacity are the bottleneck\n- the team uses GitHub Copilot App to decide which existing app gets the first agentic upgrade\n\nSo the portfolio should include a few plausible internal apps, each useful, but only one or two should obviously matter most right now.\n\n## Strong app ideas for the portfolio\n\n### 1. Supply Allocation Planner\nWhat it does:\n- takes forecast, inventory, batch schedules, and market priority inputs\n- recommends where limited product should be shipped first\n- helps balance high demand markets, launch timing, and service levels\n\nWhy it works:\n- directly connected to \"capture early market share\"\n- easy to explain visually\n- agentic upgrade is intuitive: monitor signals, propose reallocations, flag risks, draft decisions\n\nAgentic addition:\n- a Market Response Agent that watches competitor news, demand changes, inventory, and plant output\n- opens recommendation sessions automatically when conditions shift\n- proposes allocation changes with rationale and approval path\n\nThis is probably the **best choice** if you want the app triage to land on a clear business outcome fast.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Manufacturing Slot Optimizer\nWhat it does:\n- manages batch sequencing, line capacity, changeovers, QA windows, and plant schedules\n- helps ops teams decide which runs to accelerate or resequence\n\nWhy it works:\n- maps directly to the scenario line about batch release velocity and throughput\n- has strong operational tension\n- good candidate for long-running agents\n\nAgentic addition:\n- a Capacity Recovery Agent\n- detects schedule slippage, material constraints, or QA bottlenecks\n- proposes revised production sequences and escalates when GMP or yield risk rises\n\nThis is the **best choice** if the next demo after triage goes deeper into engineering and autonomous operations.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Batch Release Exception Manager\nWhat it does:\n- tracks deviations, QA review queues, document gaps, and release readiness\n- helps quality teams prioritize what is blocking product release\n\nWhy it works:\n- high value in pharma\n- speaks to compressed timelines without ignoring compliance\n- shows AI inside regulated work, which is compelling\n\nAgentic addition:\n- a Release Readiness Agent\n- gathers missing records, summarizes deviations, drafts review packets, and routes issues to the right approvers\n\nVery credible, but slightly more specialized. Great if you want a compliance-heavy angle.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Demand Signal Watchtower\nWhat it does:\n- combines market news, prescription trends, field feedback, distributor inventory, and competitor updates\n- gives commercial and supply teams an early warning view\n\nWhy it works:\n- directly tied to the breaking news trigger\n- easy to justify as the first place leadership looks\n- useful setup for downstream actions\n\nAgentic addition:\n- a Competitive Impact Agent\n- interprets launch news, updates demand scenarios, and opens issues for affected apps or teams\n\nThis is a strong supporting app, but by itself it may feel more analytical than operational unless it feeds another app.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Formulary and Market Access Tracker\nWhat it does:\n- tracks payor submission status, evidence packages, regional launch readiness, and access blockers\n- helps the company prioritize markets where access can move fastest\n\nWhy it works:\n- lines up with \"accelerate payor and formulary readiness\"\n- gives a broader enterprise feel beyond manufacturing\n\nAgentic addition:\n- a Market Access Agent\n- monitors submission gaps, drafts task lists, and highlights where accelerated supply would actually convert into patient access\n\nGood option, but probably better later in the story than as the first engineering insertion point.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Cold Chain and Distribution Control Tower\nWhat it does:\n- tracks shipment readiness, cold storage constraints, transit risk, and regional warehouse capacity\n- supports reliable delivery for injectable therapies\n\nWhy it works:\n- very plausible for pharma\n- useful if the product is temperature-sensitive\n- creates strong operational visuals\n\nAgentic addition:\n- a Distribution Exception Agent\n- spots shipment risk, proposes reroutes, and coordinates with supply allocation\n\nGood supporting candidate, though less central than capacity or allocation.\n\n## My recommendation for the demo\n\nIf the goal is to choose **one app with the highest upside**, I would present a portfolio like this:\n\n- Demand Signal Watchtower\n- Manufacturing Slot Optimizer\n- Supply Allocation Planner\n- Batch Release Exception Manager\n\nThen have the team land on:\n\n## Recommended winner: Supply Allocation Planner\n\nWhy this is the strongest choice:\n- it sits at the intersection of commercial urgency and operational constraint\n- it turns the competitor event into a concrete action\n- it is easy to explain why an agent helps\n- it can hand off cleanly into local development: build the first agent, skill, or Copilot artifact\n\n### Suggested reasoning in the demo\nYou could have the team say, in effect:\n\n- Demand Signal Watchtower tells us what changed\n- Manufacturing Slot Optimizer helps plants respond\n- Batch Release Exception Manager helps quality clear blockers\n- But the first place to add an agent is Supply Allocation Planner, because every day matters now, and we need the system to continuously rebalance limited supply toward the markets that defend share fastest\n\nThat gives a nice triage arc.\n\n## A simple \"portfolio\" you can show in Copilot App\n\nYou could make the internal app list look something like this:\n\n- `market-signal-watchtower`\n- `plant-capacity-optimizer`\n- `supply-allocation-planner`\n- `batch-release-exceptions`\n- `market-access-readiness`\n\nThen narrow on:\n\n- `supply-allocation-planner`\n\n## First concrete implementation target\n\nOnce they choose the app, the first feature should be specific and easy to build.\n\n### Best first target\n**Agent: Competitive Demand Response Agent**\n\nWhat it does:\n- monitors demand forecast changes and competitor launch inputs\n- compares those with available inventory and batch schedules\n- proposes updated market allocations\n- creates a reviewable recommendation with assumptions, tradeoffs, and required approvals\n\nInputs:\n- competitor launch timing\n- demand forecast by market\n- inventory by region\n- batch release schedule\n- plant capacity constraints\n- service level and market priority rules\n\nOutputs:\n- recommended allocation changes\n- flagged stockout risks\n- list of impacted markets\n- approval-ready summary for ops and commercial leads\n\nWhy this is a good first build:\n- concrete\n- visible\n- auditable\n- easy to connect to agent patterns and Copilot Studio artifacts\n\n## If you want a more engineering-centric choice\n\nPick **Manufacturing Slot Optimizer** and add:\n\n**Agent: Capacity Recovery Agent**\n- monitors line schedules, changeovers, QA delays, and material shortages\n- proposes schedule resequencing\n- opens work items for planners and plant teams\n\nThis will feel more technical and operational. Good if the next demo is deep in code and orchestration.\n\n## Short version I would use in the demo room\n\n\"We looked across the app portfolio and asked a simple question: where does an agent help the company respond to this launch pressure first? Demand monitoring tells us what changed. Manufacturing optimization helps plants catch up. Quality tools help release product faster. But the best first insertion point is the Supply Allocation Planner, because it sits right where demand shock meets limited supply. So the first build is a Competitive Demand Response Agent that watches demand, inventory, and capacity, then proposes where product should move next.\"\n\nIf you want, I can turn this into either:\n\n- a **clean app portfolio table** you can use in the demo, or\n- a **row-by-row rewrite** of the sketch narrative so the chosen app and reasoning are baked into the voiceover.",
      "role": "assistant"
    },
    {
      "content": "can you create a new note with these ideas? Also - thoughts on how to couch them in a collection of apps this company ostensibly already has?",
      "role": "user"
